---
title: Sliced Steak Tagliata with Sweet Potatoes, Green Beans, and Tomato Vinaigrette
description: Tagliata comes from the Italian word for “to cut,” referring to the fact that this steak is always served sliced. Legend even has it the dish originated with a particularly persnickety noblewoman who demanded that her servants do the carving for her. We’re honoring her request by slicing up sirloin before serving and drizzling it with a balsamic sauce, which dribbles onto the sweet potato wedges, soaking them in succulent juices.
